 Jāmbavant  : m.: King of bears (ṛkṣarāja 3. 264. 23; ṛkṣādhipati 3. 268. 24).<br><br>  One of the four councillors (saciva) of Sugrīva; intelligent and very strong 3. 264. 23-24; he came to help Rāma (rāmakāraṇāt) with a hundred crores of bears 3. 267. 8-9; Lakṣmaṇa, led by Vibhīṣaṇa and Jāmbavant, crashed into the southern gate of Laṅkā 3. 268. 24; he was among those who applied water, sent by Kubera, to the eyes to enable them to see invisible beings 3. 273. 13; he and other monkey-chiefs with their armies surrounded Rāvaṇa when he came out of Laṅkā to attack Rāma 3. 274. 3; besides being king of bears, he is also called chief of the apes (kapīndra) 13. 14. 24, and chief of the Vidyādharas (vidyādharendra) 13. 14. 25.<br><br><br>_______________________________<br>*1st word in left half of page p25  (+offset) in original book.

