 Indratīrtha  : nt.: Name of a tīrtha. <br><br>  A.   Location: Not far from the āśrama of Srucāvatī, daughter of Bharadvāja, near the tīrtha Badarapācana 9. 47. 17. <br><br>  B.   Description: excellent (uttama) 9. 47. 17; famous in the three worlds (triṣu lokeṣu viśrute) 9. 47. 17; auspicious (śiva) 9. 48. 5; holy (puṇya), most ancient (sanātana), which frees one of all sins (sarvapāpapramocana) 9. 48. 5. <br><br>  C.   Name: Since Indra performed there a hundred sacrifices, the tīrtha came to be known after him (tatra hy amararājo 'sāv īje kratuśatena ha… tasya nāmnā ca tat tīrtham…indratīrtham iti khyātam) 9. 48. 2, 5. <br><br>  D.   Events: (i) Epic: Balarāma, in his tīrthayātrā, went from the Badarapācanatīrtha to Indratīrtha; he took bath according to the rites and gave riches and jewels to Brāhmaṇas 9. 48. 1; Balarāma bathed there (upaspṛśya) according to the rites and honoured Brāhmaṇas by giving them drinks, clothes and food (pānācchādanabhojanaiḥ); from there he went to the Rāmatīrtha 9. 48. 6; (ii) Mythological: Indra performed there, without any hindrance, a hundred sacrifices according to the prescribed rites, rich in meat, and giving all kinds of dakṣiṇās (nirargalān sajārūthyān sarvān vividhadakṣiṇān; Nī. on Bom. Ed. 9. 49. 1: jārūthyān puṣṭān) with the help of priests versed in the Vedas; in those sacrifices he gave ample wealth to Bṛhaspati 9. 48. 2-3; (iii) Indra, after his meeting with Srucāvatī, went to the nearby Indratīrtha and began to mutter mantras (tato japyaṁ jajāpa saḥ) 9. 47. 17.<br><br><br>_______________________________<br>*5th word in left half of page p295  (+offset) in original book.

